title: Check that roots found in nlminb search for Vale & Maurelli polynomials
body:
Hi Yves,

Simple pull request which checks whether the *roots* of the required polynomials have been located rather than some potential *minimum*. It's possible for the `nlminb` optimiser to terminate successfully for some skew/kurtosis combinations, but that the solution doesn't actually contain roots, in which case a warning should be thrown. Cheers.

Phil

title: add lav_mvnorm tests
body:
I added a file to /tests that can be checked automatically by the testthat package.  The bottom line is a commented command that can be run to test only this file.  It should remain commented so that recursion does not produce a spurious error).

The file only includes tests for the family of tests (1.) that returns (sums of) (log-)densities, comparing the output from several options with the manually coded use of mvtnorm and mnormt packages.  If I find software that returns derivatives, I could add those tests, but for now I will simply compare the source code to the documentation. 

Terry

title: Removing three references in Imports and NAMESPACE
body:
Hi Yves, your package has made my life easier by including it in our package: http://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/NlsyLinks/index.html.  

I noticed R-Forge was griping that lavaan wasn't available (https://r-forge.r-project.org/R/?group_id=1330&log=build_src&pkg=NlsyLinks&flavor=patched).  I'm not sure why, because it's available for my Win8 and Ubuntu13.04 boxes without a problem.

Nevertheless, I came over here to see what could explain R-Forge's griping.  I didn't see any problems serious enough, but I thought I'd try to address some of the namespace and imports warnings that R CMD CHECK produced.  Depending on your setup, you probably don't care about the Rproj file and the two ignores.  R CMD CHECK had two other warnings that I mentioned in my first commit.

I hope this saves you more time than it costs you, and my feelings won't be hurt if they're ignored. -Will Beasley

title: Regular expressions updates in parseModelString
body:
Hi Yves,

Great to see you in Connecticut, and I hope your trip home was uneventful. I took a quick look at parseModelString and made a few improvements to the use of regular expressions in the first chunk. I didn't have a chance to walk through the whole parser, just the first 10-15 lines. Anyway, the tweaks here improved the speed of the routine by about 5% on my machine -- not that it was particularly costly to begin with. I'll try to work through the rest of the parser with an eye toward improving the regular expression usage and efficiency.

Hope that helps,
Michael

title: Coef change
body:
Yves,  I figured I'd try a pull request for the first time on something fairly minor.  All I've done is change the coef function so that there is now a show.all argument so that other functions can get all coefficients and their labels.  This is so that, in, say, the new difftest function, one doesn't need to get both the est and label slots, but can rather just use the coef function.

But, yeah, first time doing a github pull request.  Let's see how this goes!

-Jarrett
